We notice a population imbalance, so now we merged with covariates so we can model on PC

totaldata=merge(combined_data,covs,by.x="ID",by.y="person_id")

dim(totaldata)
## [1] 225577     24
pcmod=lm(PRS~PC1+PC2+PC3+PC4+PC5,data = totaldata)
totaldata$predictscore=predict(object = pcmod,newdata=totaldata)
totaldata$residscore=(totaldata$PRS-totaldata$predictscore)
totaldata$Population=as.factor(totaldata$Population)

We can scale the scores by all populatios jointly but note that SAS is depleted and EAS slightly enriched for high risk PRS:

Note that there are three choices for PRS, we can use :

  • the overall (unscaled) residual,

  • the scaled (overall residuals),

  • the population scaled residual

  • Here we use the populations scaled residuals

library(tidyr)
populations <- levels(as.factor(totaldat$Population))
library(survival)
#Initialize an empty list for storing models and results
cox_models <- list()
glm_models = list()


# Before the loop
results <- data.frame(
  Population = character(),
  PRS_Mean = numeric(),
  PRS_SD = numeric(),
  Percent_male = numeric(),
  LDL_Coef_CI_Lower = numeric(),
  LDL_Coef_CI_Upper = numeric(),
  Population_Scale_Factor = numeric(),
  LDL_Scaled_Coef_CI_Lower = numeric(),
  LDL_Scaled_Coef_CI_Upper = numeric(),
  HR=numeric(),
  HR_CI_Lower = numeric(),
  HR_CI_Upper = numeric(),
  OR = numeric(),
  OR_LCI = numeric(),
  OR_UCI = numeric(),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

for (pop in populations) {
  # Your existing data subsetting and model fitting code here

  pop_data <- subset(totaldat, Population == pop)
  pop_data$PRS <- pop_data$pop_scaled_prs
  #pop_data$sex <- factor(ifelse(pop_data$sex_report == "Male", 1, 0))
  pop_data$sex <- factor(ifelse(pop_data$sex_at_birth.x == "Male", 1, 0))
    # Linear Regression for LDL-C Levels
  ldl_model <- lm(max_measurement ~ PRS + as.numeric(age) + sex +  PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC9 +
        PC10, data = pop_data[!is.na(pop_data$max_measurement),])

  ## scale the prs
  prs_scale_factor <- 40 / coef(ldl_model)["PRS"]
  pop_data$scaled_ldl_prs <- pop_data$PRS / prs_scale_factor
  
  ## show that it's correct
  ldl_model_2 <- lm(max_measurement ~ scaled_ldl_prs + as.numeric(age) + sex +  PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC9 +
        PC10, data =  pop_data[!is.na(pop_data$max_measurement),])
  
  ldl_scaled_coef_ci <- confint(ldl_model_2, "scaled_ldl_prs")

  # Cox or GLM for CAD: for cox you DO NOT control for age since it's in tere
  cox_model <- coxph(Surv(total_censor_age, total_pheno) ~ scaled_ldl_prs + sex +  PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC9 +PC10, data = pop_data)
  
  glm_model <- glm(total_pheno ~ scaled_ldl_prs + as.numeric(age) + sex +  PC1 + PC2 + PC3 + PC4 + PC5 + PC6 + PC7 + PC8 + PC9 +
        PC10, data = pop_data, family = "binomial")
  
    log_or = summary(glm_model)$coefficients["scaled_ldl_prs", "Estimate"]
  log_or_se = summary(glm_model)$coefficients["scaled_ldl_prs", "Std. Error"]
  or = round(exp(log_or), 2)
  glmci=confint(glm_model)
  lci = round(exp(log_or - 1.96 * log_or_se), 2)
  uci = round(exp(log_or + 1.96 * log_or_se), 2)
  
  cox_summary <- summary(cox_model)
  glm_summary <- summary(glm_model)
  
  cox_models[[pop]] <- cox_model
  glm_models[[pop]] = glm_model

  # Calculate PRS mean and standard deviation
  prs_mean <- mean(pop_data$PRS)
  prs_sd <- sd(pop_data$PRS)
  
  
  # Calculate Male/Female ratio or any other appropriate sex summary
  sex_male <- mean(pop_data$sex == 1) 

  # Extract LDL model coefficients and CI directly
  ldl_coef_ci <- confint(ldl_model, "PRS")
  
  # Adjust for scale factor and re-calculate for scaled model if needed
  
  # Cox and GLM model summaries for HR and OR, with CIs
  
  # Append to results
  results <- rbind(results, data.frame(
    Population = pop,
    PRS_Mean = prs_mean,
    PRS_SD = prs_sd,
    Percent_male = sex_male,
    LDL_Coef_CI_Lower = ldl_coef_ci[1],
    LDL_Coef_CI_Upper = ldl_coef_ci[2],
    Population_Scale_Factor = prs_scale_factor,
    LDL_Scaled_Coef_CI_Lower = ldl_scaled_coef_ci[1], # Adjust according to your calculations
    LDL_Scaled_Coef_CI_Upper = ldl_scaled_coef_ci[2],
    HR = cox_summary$conf.int["scaled_ldl_prs", 1],
    HR_CI_Lower = cox_summary$conf.int["scaled_ldl_prs", 3], # Assuming 'cox_summary' is properly defined
    HR_CI_Upper = cox_summary$conf.int["scaled_ldl_prs", 4], # Assuming 'cox_summary' is properly defined
    OR = or,
    # OR_LCI = lci,
    # OR_UCI = uci
    # 
       
    OR_LCI = exp(glmci['scaled_ldl_prs',1]),
    OR_UCI = exp(glmci['scaled_ldl_prs',2])
  ))
}
